      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Why Engineers Use Millimeters Instead of Centimeters</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 16, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>If you have ever looked at an engineering drawing, you will notice all dimensions are in millimeters — not centimeters, not meters, not inches. A bracket might be labelled "45.5" without any unit, and everyone in the field knows it means 45.5 mm. Why is this the convention?</p>

      <h2>The Practical Reasons</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Whole numbers for most parts:</strong> Most manufactured parts have dimensions between 1 and 1000 mm. Using mm means you rarely need decimal points for standard tolerance work (a 25 mm bolt, not 2.5 cm or 0.025 m)</li>
        <li><strong>Eliminates decimal confusion:</strong> Writing "2.5 cm" risks misreading the decimal as "25 cm" — a 10x error. Writing "25 mm" has no ambiguity</li>
        <li><strong>One unit throughout:</strong> When everything is in mm, you never mix up cm and m on the same drawing</li>
        <li><strong>International standard:</strong> ISO 129 and ISO 80000 specify mm as the preferred unit for engineering drawings</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Decimal Problem</h2>
      <p>Consider three ways to write the same dimension:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>0.0375 m — four decimal places, easy to misread</li>
        <li>3.75 cm — requires a decimal point</li>
        <li>37.5 mm — clean, readable, fewer digits</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In a workshop environment with grease, poor lighting, and time pressure, the clearest notation wins. Millimeters give you whole numbers or simple one-decimal values for almost everything you would machine, print, or fabricate.</p>

      <h2>When Precision Goes Further</h2>
      <p>For high-precision work, engineers use decimal millimeters:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Standard machining: ±0.1 mm tolerance</li>
        <li>Precision machining: ±0.01 mm tolerance</li>
        <li>Grinding/lapping: ±0.001 mm (1 micrometre)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Even at micrometre precision, it is written as 25.003 mm rather than switching to a different unit. Consistency reduces errors.</p>

      <h2>What About Other Industries?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> Uses mm in metric countries (a wall might be 2400 mm tall)</li>
        <li><strong>Electronics:</strong> PCB design uses mm (component pads at 0.5 mm pitch)</li>
        <li><strong>3D Printing:</strong> Slicers and CAD software default to mm</li>
        <li><strong>Construction (US):</strong> Still uses feet, inches, and fractions (1/16")</li>
        <li><strong>Aerospace:</strong> Often uses inches in the US, mm elsewhere</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Converting Between Units</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1 mm = 0.1 cm = 0.001 m</li>
        <li>1 mm = 0.03937 inches</li>
        <li>1 inch = 25.4 mm (exact)</li>
        <li>10 mm = 1 cm</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The relationship between mm and inches is especially important because many legacy parts are still dimensioned in imperial. The exact conversion (25.4 mm per inch) makes dual-dimensioning straightforward.</p>

